---
title: "TypeScript Language Practices"
description: "Standards for writing robust, readable TypeScript"
tags: [typescript, language]
---

## Types and Interfaces
- Prefer explicit function signatures and exported types.
- Avoid `any`; use unions, generics, and discriminated unions.
- Narrow types with type guards early; prefer `unknown` to `any` for inputs.

## Control Flow
- Use guard clauses and early returns.
- Avoid deep nesting beyond two levels.
- Handle errors meaningfully; avoid empty catches.

## Modules and Imports
- Use path aliases consistently; avoid relative path hell.
- Keep module public APIs small and well-named.

## Async and Promises
- Use `async/await`; handle errors with `try/catch` or `.catch`.
- Avoid floating promises; use `void` only where safe.

## Linting and Formatting
- Enforce ESLint with strict rules; Prettier for consistent formatting.
- No unused variables or eslint disables without rationale.

## Validation Checklist
- [ ] Public APIs typed; no `any`
- [ ] Errors handled; no silent failures
- [ ] Imports clean and deduped
- [ ] Lint passes; formatting consistent

